    title: "Alcohol Use Disorder",
    cellular: "Alcohol is a CNS depressant acting primarily on GABA and glutamate systems. Alcohol enhances GABA inhibition and inhibits NMDA glutamate excitation. Chronic use leads to neuroadaptation: GABA downregulation and glutamate upregulation, causing CNS hyperexcitability during withdrawal. Alcohol withdrawal can be life-threatening: onset 6-24 hours after last drink, progressing through tremors, anxiety, diaphoresis, tachycardia, to potentially seizures (12-48 hours) and delirium tremens (48-96 hours, 5% mortality untreated). The CIWA-Ar (Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment for Alcohol) guides withdrawal management. AUDIT screening identifies hazardous drinking. MAT options include naltrexone (oral or injectable), acamprosate, and disulfiram.",
